Rating: 4
This chowder is delicious! I substituted a large shallot for the leeks (none at the store that day) and added some chopped celery at the same time. I also used baby reds instead of the russet potato and simmered covered for about 15 minutes, then simmered uncovered for 5 minutes after adding oysters. I actually used drained, smoked oysters (3.75 ounce tin) since that is what I had on hand. I also used fat-free 1/2 & 1/2 to cut back on some calories, and seafood broth instead of clam juice. The consistency of the broth was perfect and the smokiness of the chowder was outstanding!

Rating: 4
Really good. Used smoked oysters...coconut milk as dairy alternative, no bacon, homemade chicken stock...great!

Rating: 3
OK,so it's sort of winter here and I saw the ouysters calling out to me, so they ended up in my basket. My mother taught me to make oyster stew a long time ago, so I sort of merged this recipe and that. The only differences were using leeks instead of onions (which I did) and the addition of the potatoes. The one difference I would highly recommend would be to add about 3 tablespoons of Worcestershire Sauce, just to give it a little more kick and flavor. It doesn't cover up the oysters like a lot of additions would.

